Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario (requires MSTest 3.9–3.10+):

**1. Windows-only tests** — `[OSCondition]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\MyApp", "Version", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

**2. Skip in CI** — `[CICondition]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void GpuRenderer_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    var result = GpuRenderer.Render(scene);
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

**3. Flaky external API** — `[Retry]`
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
{
    var forecast = await _weatherClient.GetForecastAsync(_testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(forecast);
}
```
Use `[Retry]` only for genuinely flaky external dependencies — not to mask race conditions or shared-state bugs.

**4. Cleanup on failure** — `[TestCleanup]` or `IDisposable`
```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class TempFileTests : IDisposable
{
    private readonly string _tempFile;

    public TempFileTests()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void ProcessFile_WritesExpectedContent()
    {
        FileProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        Assert.AreEqual("expected", File.ReadAllText(_tempFile));
    }

    // Runs even if the test fails — guaranteed cleanup
    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

You can also use `[TestCleanup]` instead of `IDisposable` — both run after each test regardless of pass/fail. `IDisposable` is idiomatic C# and enables `readonly` fields; `[TestCleanup]` is useful when you need async cleanup (`ValueTask`/`Task` return).
